    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1925-01-14T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1925-01-14T14:00:00-05:00" n="601"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d601">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.162/9: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Salvador</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Schuyler</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">San Salvador</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1925-01-14T13:00:00-06:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 14, 1925—1 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received 10:20 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2. Referring to most-favored-nation exchange of notes. The Minister for Foreign
                    Affairs suggests informally as <hi rend="italic">quid pro quo</hi> that United
                    States shall grant Salvadorean and preferably all Central American sugar same
                    rates as now given Cuban sugar. I have explained fully peculiar reciprocal
                    nature of article 8 of our commercial convention with Cuba but he requests that
                    I forward his suggestion to you.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Schuyler</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
